{"author":{"id":"75732e82453cc4795a3b5d7bef7a9ce916b428e5bbe06161843f7392657be5c1"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1444979592,"nonce":"39PUUZqofw6IFwVQ7DaPD9Z0pl0=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDE0ODYzNDUxMw==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/332#issuecomment-148634513"},"message":"If I remember correctly, the extensive output contains comment lines that start with a hashtag.\n\nI think comment lines and a header line are two different properties of a table, and using such hacks may introduce problems at the long term. Imagine that the definition of tabular files once gets an extra metadata feature for header-lines, then for backwards compatibility you always have to check comment lines too. So I would only go for a metadata check if the metadata explicitly describes that it contains a header line.\n\nWhat @mvdbeek proposes seems more logical to me. I know R can be nasty with automatically checking this because the number of columns in the headerline must be 1 smaller than the other lines, so the most logical way to me should be to manually check if the 2nd element of the 1st row is numerical. If we do this we should make sure that all these genes are kicked out:\n\n```\nexclude_HTSeq \u003c- c(\"no_feature\",\"ambiguous\",\"too_low_aQual\",\"not_aligned\",\"alignment_not_unique\")\nexclude_DEXSeq \u003c- c(\"_ambiguous\",\"_empty\",\"_lowaqual\",\"_notaligned\")\n```\n\nThose of HTSeq I once checked, so they should be fine.","files":null}]}